We recommended that the City Mayor direct:
The City Engineer to –
conduct an in-depth assessment of the work status of existing projects and to impose the penalties and sanctions provided under Annexes “E” and “I” of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 for those undertaken by contracts or to prioritize the completion of unfinished projects undertaken by administration;
improve the execution and monitoring of projects to exact compliance to project timelines by adopting stricter policies to eliminate any negative slippage noted and a detailed action to commit contractors to accomplish specific physical targets over a defined time period;
assign a project engineer who shall be responsible for the close supervision and reporting of the project to which he is assigned, so that proper accountability could be easily determined, as warranted;
The Project Monitoring Committee to –
determine accountability for the losses sustained by the government due to projects undertaken by administration which could not anymore be put to viable use with the passage of time;
improve the quality of information in its monitoring reports by eliminating projects which were already reported as completed in the prior years and maintaining an updated database that highlights those which were completed during the year, still on-going and/or behind schedule; and
attach to the quarterly report a certification of extensions/ suspensions granted, if any, supported by a certified copy thereof.

One out of the six recommendations were fully implemented in 2020.  The unimplemented recommendation are as follows:

We recommended that the City Mayor direct:

(a)	The City Engineer to –

i)	conduct an in-depth assessment of the work status of existing projects and to impose the penalties and sanctions provided under Annexes “E” and “I” of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 for those undertaken by contracts or to prioritize the completion of unfinished projects undertaken by administration;

ii)	improve the execution and monitoring of projects to exact compliance to project timelines by adopting stricter policies to eliminate any negative slippage noted and a detailed action to commit contractors to accomplish specific physical targets over a defined time period;

(b)	The Project Monitoring Committee to – 

i)	determine accountability for the losses sustained by the government due to projects undertaken by administration which could not anymore be put to viable use with the passage of time;

ii)	improve the quality of information in its monitoring reports by eliminating projects which were already reported as completed in the prior years and maintaining an updated database that highlights those which were completed during the year, still on-going and/or behind schedule; and

iii)	attach to the quarterly report a certification of extensions/ suspensions granted, if any, supported by a certified copy thereof.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

a)	Direct the City Engineer, City Planning and Development Coordinator and/or other officials involved to submit a written explanation for the deficiencies noted, why projects undertaken by administration were not immediately corrected, with proof that no funds were released for the unfinished scope of work, or why contractors were allowed to claim progress and final payments despite the negative slippage and non-delivery of the project specifications;

Exercise the remedies provided under Section 8.4, Annex “E” of the RIRR in addressing the contracts under default, impose and collect liquidated damages in accordance with Section 8.5 thereof and avail of the remedies under Annex “I” of the RIRR for projects that have not delivered the project requirements within the contract period;

Justify the additional indirect cost incurred for projects undertaken by administration and why the same should not be regarded as unnecessary expenses which are not allowed under COA Circular No. 2012-003; and

Implement measures and undertake catch-up programs to accelerate work accomplishments so that any delays may be promptly corrected and other courses of action/remedies may be availed of.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
a) The City Engineer who certified the accomplishment of the declogging works and the Assistant City Engineer who certified the payroll submit a quantification of the work done, justify the seemingly excessive man-days and corresponding payments made, and to substantiate declogging works with pictures taken during actual project implementation;
b) The City Engineering Office, henceforth, prepare detailed Programs of Work with the exact location and quantified output indicated and with realistic cost estimates that would maximize the funds allocated for a specific project, complete with the plans and drawings as warranted;
c) Management consider charging routinary declogging expenses to the General Fund Proper based on a valid POW and to refrain from appropriating the 20% DF for non-capital or non-investment expenditures;
d) The City Development Council find more meaningful and useful projects on which to spend the bulk of its funds, which should mainly be capital in nature, in order to avoid wasteful use thereof as well as speed up the development of the City, in compliance with DILG- DBM JMC No. 2017-1; and
e) The City Accountant prepare a journal entry to adjust the asset and expense accounts for the actual declogging expenses incurred.

We recommended that the LGU
a) Terminate the contract for default following the procedures outlined under the Annex I of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184, without prejudice to other courses of action and remedies available under the circumstances;
b) File a claim with Stronghold Insurance Company, Inc. to recover the advance payment made to YSL Builders;
c) Impose the maximum of 10% as liquidated damages on YSL Builders in accordance with Section 8.5, Annex I of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
d) Furnish our office a copy of the performance security posted by the contractor, if any, and forfeit the same in favor of the City government; otherwise, if there is none, direct the members of the Bids and Awards Committee to explain in writing the lack thereof;
e) Direct the City Engineer or City Planning and Development Coordinator to submit a written explanation why no immediate steps were undertaken to address this deficiency; and
f) Implement measures and establish coordination mechanisms to ensure that projects are closely monitored so that any delays may be promptly corrected and other courses of action/remedies may be availed of.

We recommended that:
a) The Inventory Committee and the CGSO reconcile the results thereof with the accounting records, prepare the report for submission to our office and pinpoint responsibility for missing properties;
b) The CGSO secure all copies of the ARE and update the filing thereof, ensuring that these are principally considered especially during the separation of accountable officers from the government service;
c) Management update the schedule of PPE additions and disposals for CY 2017, complete with data on the property tag, ARE, accountable officer, and office/location of the equipment, otherwise, those that cannot be accounted for shall be accordingly disallowed; and
d) The City Accountant attach the formatted and detailed schedule of PPE additions and disposals to the yearly financial report of the LGU and regularly update it to facilitate the conduct of the physical inventory and the determination of accountability for government properties.

RECOMMENDATION
We recommended the allocation of at least one percent of the IRA for the programs of the LCPC, the creation of a CIMTF and the activation and strengthening of the LCPC through the following measures:
a.  Requiring the LCPC to conduct regular and special meetings at least once every two months to discuss issues and problems on children and to come up with strategies for their implementation;
b.  Requiring the LCPC to maintain an updated database of children as basis for the preparation of the AWFP for the amount allocated, which should be submitted to and approved by the local sanggunian;
c.  Specifying the responsibilities of each of the members of the LCPC and the management and referral of children in need of protection and assistance, as well as the conduct of follow-up; and
d.  Requiring the LCPC to perform their mandated functions and submit the required plans as enumerated under Sec. 3 of DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2008-126 dated August 21, 2008.
